<subSubSection lastPageId="25" lastPageNumber="26" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1437,259,1042]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,763,789]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Remarks.</emphasis>
De 
<bibRefCitation author="Laubenfels, M. W. de" box="[366,574,763,790]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="1 - 154" refId="ref78070" refString="Laubenfels, M. W. de (1950) The Porifera of the Bermuda Archipielago. Transactions of the Zoological Society of London, 27, 1 - 154. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1950. tb 00227. x" type="journal article" year="1950">Laubenfels (1950)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Rutzler" authorityYear="1974" box="[700,830,763,790]" class="Demospongiae" family="Clionaidae" genus="Cliona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="dioryssa">
<emphasis box="[700,830,763,790]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">C. dioryssa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Laubenfels" authorityYear="1950" box="[871,1107,763,789]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spirastrellidae" genus="Spirastrella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clionaida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="dioryssa">
<emphasis box="[871,1107,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Spirastrella dioryssa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[1147,1261,763,789]" name="Bermuda" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Bermudas</collectingCountry>
(
<typeStatus box="[1277,1327,763,789]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">type</typeStatus>
locality), whose main characteristic is the stout spirasters in two categories. However, de Laubenfels’ description was relatively brief regarding the characteristics and measurements of the spirasters (
<tableCitation box="[1022,1111,835,861]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="24.[151,239,1089,1113]" captionText="TABLE 2. Cliona dioryssa, color and spicule dimensions reported in the literature and current records. Micrometric data is presented as minimum–maximum length/minimum–maximum thickness; in µm." pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Table 2</tableCitation>
). Later, 
<bibRefCitation author="Rutzler, K." box="[1205,1370,835,861]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="32" refId="ref80398" refString="Rutzler, K. (1974) The Burrowing Sponges of Bermuda. Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 165, 32. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00810282.165" type="journal article" year="1974">Rützler (1974)</bibRefCitation>
redescribed the species more extensively in his revision “The borrowing sponges of 
<collectingCountry box="[1077,1185,871,897]" name="Bermuda" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
”, where the spirasters were reported as – 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<typeStatus box="[354,406,908,933]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Type</typeStatus>
<taxonomicName box="[413,485,908,933]" class="Demospongiae" family="Iotrochotidae" genus="Iotrochota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="stout">I stout</taxonomicName>
, with a thick shaft densely set with large strong spines, most of which are joined at the base. 
<typeStatus box="[217,269,944,969]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Type</typeStatus>
II is more delicate, with a long slender shaft and small spines, which are usually well spaced from each other. Reduction of number or size of spines is very common
</emphasis>
–. Our specimen’s spirasters match with the description given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Rutzler, K." box="[255,422,1015,1041]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="32" refId="ref80398" refString="Rutzler, K. (1974) The Burrowing Sponges of Bermuda. Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 165, 32. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00810282.165" type="journal article" year="1974">Rützler (1974)</bibRefCitation>
, but the spirasters II in our material are longer (
<tableCitation box="[955,1043,1015,1041]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="24.[151,239,1089,1113]" captionText="TABLE 2. Cliona dioryssa, color and spicule dimensions reported in the literature and current records. Micrometric data is presented as minimum–maximum length/minimum–maximum thickness; in µm." pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Table 2</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
